<1ST_LINE>u a AM-JailDisturbance     12-24 0200</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Jail Disturbance,0205</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Inmates, Upset About Christmas Eve Detention, Set Fires At Georgia
Jail</HEAD>
<DATELINE>GAINESVILLE, Ga. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Inmates at the Hall County jail,
apparently upset about being locked up on Christmas Eve, staged a
protest Saturday night, setting fires and causing an undetermined
amount of damage before the uprising was ended, authorities said.
   The disturbance, which began about 8:30 p.m., was under control
by 11:30 p.m., said Sgt. Ed Barfield, spokesman for the Hall County
Sheriff's Department. There were no injuries, he said.
   ``They were disgruntled,'' Barfield said. ``It's overcrowded
here; we've got them one on top of another. It's Christmas. They
were just disgruntled.''
   Barfield said the disturbance occurred in a cell block housing
about 30 inmates. He said he did not know how many participated in
the unrest.
   The inmates set fires to mattresses, and ``a good bit of damage''
was done to light fixtures and air ducts, he said. There also was
considerable water damage.
   Barfield said a county SWAT team, as well as city police and
state corrections officials, were called in to help quell the
disturbance.
   Officers planned to stay on the scene Sunday morning in case
there was a recurrence, he said.
</TEXT>
