<1ST_LINE>u i BC-Lebanon-Captives     12-25 0208</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Lebanon-Captives,0215</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Relatives of Captive Girls Meet With Kidnappers</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Relatives of two French girls held captive
by Palestinian guerrillas more than a year met with a representative
of the kidnappers Sunday, the day after the kidnappers promised to
release them.
   The meeting took place at the office of Walid Khaled, the
spokesman of the Fatah-Revolutionary Council group, in the Mar Elias
Palestinian refugee camp in West Beirut.
   An unidentified French reporter accompanying the relatives came
out of the meeting and told reporters that Khaled told them: ``We
shall release the two girls along with a videotape.''
   It was not clear when the girls, Marie-Laure, 7, and Virginie, 6,
daughters of Jacqueline Valente, would be released.
   The Fatah-Revolutionary Council, headed by reputed terrorist Abu
Nidal, declared Nov. 8, 1987 it had seized the girls, their French
mother and five Belgian adults aboard a French yacht off the Gaza
Strip.
   The group said Saturday the girls would be released within 24
hours.
   The meeting was attended by Ms. Valente's mother, Brigitte
Valente, her former husband Pascal Batille and brother-in-law Andre
Metral.
   The Fatah statement said the girls would be released in response
to an appeal from Libyan leader Col. Moammar Ghadafi, the group's
main backer.
</TEXT>
