<1ST_LINE>r i AM-BRF--RedChristmas     12-25 0150</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-BRF--Red Christmas,0152</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Cloud of Thick, Red Dust Covers Khartoum</HEAD>
<DATELINE>KHARTOUM, Sudan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A cloud of thick, red dust stirred by
strong winds significantly reduced visibility in the capital Sunday
and marred Christmas celebrations for many Sudanese who
traditionally spend the day picnicking.
   Mohamed Mussa, an official with the Sudanese meteorological
department, told The Associated Press the dust storm and winds would
last at least through the day.
   Mussa said visibility was 200 yards, ``which surely means planes
cannot land in the airport today until the dust has been blown
away.'' The weather also created huge traffic jams.
   The dust storm started Saturday, making breathing difficult for
many Sudanese and covering everything, including people, with thick
red and white dust.
   Although more than 90 percent of the Sudanese are Moslems, many
join their Christian friends in Christmas celebrations by driving
into the countryside outside of Khartoum for picnics.
</TEXT>
