<1ST_LINE>r a AM-ChristmasBriefs     12-25 0720</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Christmas Briefs,0745</2ND_LINE>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SLIDELL, La. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   It wasn't the baby in the manger but the one
frolicking on the grass that stole the show at First Baptist
Church's live nativity scene.
   The female donkey foal, named Star of Bethlehem for the patch of
white on her forehead, was born Wednesday just before the volunteers
who care for the animals arrived at work.
   ``I walked in the shed with a whole bunch of hay for them and
when I dropped it on the ground, I noticed (the mare) was all muddy.
Then I saw the foal,'' said Brenda Kirkley. ``I screamed, `We had
our baby!'''
   ``We knew she was pregnant _ but we didn't think she was that
pregnant,'' said Bobby Roundtree, in charge of the donkeys, camels,
ponies, sheep and a calf used in the elaborate production that
concluded Friday night.
   Most of the animals came from farms in the parish, but the camels
were from a circus in Oklahoma and the ponies, which had been
abandoned on land in Madisonville, were loaned by the St. Tammany
Parish Sheriff's Office.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>DODGE CITY, Kan. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Santa Claus impostor is wanted by Dodge
City police for a Christmas Day holdup.
   A man wearing a Santa Claus suit walked into the Kindsvater Truck
Lines Sunday morning and forced an employee to hand over an
undisclosed amount of money, said police Officer Neil Baltazor.
   ``We don't think there were any reindeer involved,'' Baltazor
said. ``He (Santa) was last seen fleeing the scene on foot.''
   The employee, who was not identified, was slightly injured during
a scuffle, Baltazor said.
   ``I guess it's an appropriate way to disguise, but it takes one
damn sick individual to rob someone on Christmas,'' said Tom
Kindsvater, co-owner of the trucking company.
   The business, which is open 24 hours a day, sells diesel fuel to
truckers. It is owned by Kindsvater and his brother, Dennis
Kindsvater.
   ``Santa Claus seems to have changed his image,'' Kindsvater said.
``We think it was someone who used to work at the place because when
he left he said, `Tell Tom and Dennis Merry Christmas.'''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>MONTPELIER, Vt. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   When the gifts are gone and the tinsel
tucked away, what do you do with your Christmas tree? Throw it in
the yard and watch it rot? Put it on the curb for the garbage truck?
   This year, the state of Vermont wants residents to do something
different: try recycling.
   The Agency of Natural Resources is sponsoring the $5,000
experiment, under which Vermonters will bring their trees to one of
nine locations. There state and city workers will chop the tree into
chips for use in parks or other landscaping projects.
   ``We're hoping for a positive response, particularly from the
areas where it's more densely populated, where people don't have big
backyards where they can dump their Christmas trees to degrade by
themselves,'' said Connie Leach, the agency's chief of recycling and
resource conservation section.
   Trees that are tossed out with the trash can overload garbage
trucks and landfills, Leach said.
   ``A lot of people throw them away and it's a problem for the
haulers that have packer trucks because if you can imagine a tree
getting into that packing mechanism, it really gets jammed,'' Leach
said.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>TULSA, Okla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Santa must have been flattered but a bit
confused when he made his Christmas Eve visit to Mollie Williford's
home.
   Some 2,000 replicas of himself were waiting for Santa, along with
eight Christmas trees.
   Ms. Williford's home is a virtual Santa Claus museum. Starting in
November, the Santas are brought down in 75 or so boxes from the
attic to take up shelf and tree space in nearly every room on the
first floor.
   ``Santas make me happy,'' Ms. Williford said. ``It's also a
marvelous thing to collect. And they only come out once a year.''
   They are made in all sizes, materials and shapes. They are
diverse with a Henry Ford theme: You can have it in any color, as
long as it's red and white.
   Ms. Williford's first Santa _ a tree ornament _ was bought 30
years ago, when she lived in Wichita Falls, Texas. More than 100
Santas join the collection every year; 50 or 60 of them are gifts.
</TEXT>
