<HEAD>Explosion in West Beirut, One Injured</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: New thruout to UPDATE with cause of blast, one injured. No
pickup.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A small bomb exploded under a car parked
in a residential district of Syrian-policed west Beirut Sunday,
setting cars on fire and slightly injuring one man, police said.
   A police spokesman said the bomb went off at 6:10 p.m. near the
fire brigade headquarters in the Moslem sector's Tarik Jedideh
district.
   An ambulance evacuated the wounded man to the nearby Makassed
Hospital, said the spokesman, who cannot be named under standing
regulations.
   The explosion set two parked cars on fire, the spokesman said,
adding that firefighters quickly extinguished the blaze.
   An eyewitness, speaking on condition of anonymity, said helmeted
Syrian troops sealed off the blast scene immediately after the
explosion, and some fired their automatic rifles in the air to keep
civilians away.
   No group claimed responsibility for the blast, which appeared to
be another in a series of bombings designed to discredit Syria's
role as law enforcers in the Moslem sector of the divided capital.
   Syria maintains about 40,000 troops in Lebanon under a
12-year-old Arab League peacekeeping mandate.
</TEXT>
