<FILEID>AP-NR-12-25-88 1404EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u a AM-Russia-Watcher 1stLd-Writethru a0691 12-25 0848</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Russia-Watcher, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0691,800</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>With Laserphoto WX6</NOTE>
<NOTE>EDs: subs 7th graf to correct spelling of bated; subs 15th graf to
fix typo in lieutenant; subs 19th graf to conform Rand to style</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By BRYAN BRUMLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ALEXANDRIA, Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Lt. Gen. William Odom spent much of his
Army career immersed in the Soviet Union, including three years as
head of the supersecret National Security Agency that eavesdrops on
U.S. adversaries.
   In retirement, he's still pursuing his life's interest, writing
scholarly articles, watching the changes in the Soviet Union,
preparing to teach Soviet politics at Yale University and reading
his favorite Russian literature.
   As director of national security studies at the Hudson Institute,
a think tank with offices near Washington, Odom writes on relations
between the Soviet Union's civilian and military leaders, a longtime
expertise that has taken on new urgency because of Mikhail
Gorbachev's reforms of the Red Army.
   Odom emerged from bureaucratic shadows into national headlines in
May 1986 when he gruffly warned the news media not to speculate on
details of secrets that former NSA employee Ronald W. Pelton was
convicted of selling to the Soviets.
   Nowadays Odom, whose 34-year Army career included teaching
Russian history at West Point, has a professorial demeanor, lacing
his conversation with scholarly references. But he has not changed
his tough views toward the Soviet Union and is reserving judgment
about whether Gorbachev can hold on.
   ``I am waiting with bated breath to see whether Gorbachev can
make it stick,'' Odom said in an interview. ``The situation as I see
it is that the lines are drawn on the military issue between the
general staff and Gorbachev's reformers.''
   Odom, 56, said that after retiring from the Army and leaving his
job as NSA director last July he has found time to enjoy two of his
favorite Russian writers, Anton Chekhov and Mikhail Zoshchenko.
   As he prepares to begin teaching at Yale in January, he continues
to write scholarly articles, including one for Foreign Policy
magazine on Gorbachev's efforts to reform the Red Army.
   That article attracted attention in the wake of Gorbachev's
announcement on Dec. 7 that he was cutting Soviet forces by about 10
percent and withdrawing 50,000 troops from Eastern Europe.
   Odom's interest in Russia began in 1953 during his third year as
a student at West Point, studying the reforms of Peter the Great
(1672-1725).
   He was assigned to the U.S. 6th Cavalry in West Germany in 1956
when that unit prepared to mobilize during the Hungarian uprising
but stayed put as Soviet tanks crushed the rebellion.
   ``My view of my duty as a second lieutenant was that I was in
Europe to hold up the Iron Curtain and to make sure that it did not
fall on Western Europe,'' Odom said.
   His interest in the Soviet Union grew, and he studied the nation
and the Russian language. In the mid-1960s he spent two years at the
military liaison office in Potsdam, East Germany, where he had a
brief chat with the commander of the Group of Soviet Forces in
Germany.
   ``You have very interesting work. I know what your job is,'' the
Soviet told Odom. ``It is to keep track of the daily activities of
the Soviet Army and report to your headquarters.''
   As a lieutenant colonel, Odom spent a year in Vietnam, working
for the military assistance command on pacification, ``understanding
why it wouldn't work'' and being a secret critic of the U.S. role in
Vietnam.
   ``I was never an enthusiast for the policy there, but for reasons
extraordinarily different from those of most people,'' he said.
   ``At Columbia (University) in graduate school, I learned there
was a Sino-Soviet split, and when I looked at the Eurasian land
mass, it occured to me that it was not in the U.S. interest to
contain China ... but that it was in Soviet interest.
   ``I found it very difficult to explain why we would commit a half
a million troops to suit Soviet foreign policy,'' he said. ``As a
lieutenant colonel, you do not really influence policy ... and I was
not sufficiently naive to be believe that I could.''
   After Vietnam, Odom wrote an article for which he is famous among
Sovietologists, a response to a theory by Rand Corp. analyst Roman
Kolkowicz that Communist Party officials and military officers
``have a conflict relationship.''
   Odom responded by noting that most senior military officers were
also Communist Party members and that although there are some
differences of opinion, party discipline prevails.
   In 1972, still a lieutenant colonel, Odom was assigned to the
U.S. Embassy in Moscow, from which he traveled through each of the
15 Soviet republics, ``staying abreast of the Soviet military. I
spent a lot of time on trains.''
   In 1977, he went to the White House as military aide to Zbigniew
Brzezinski, national security adviser to President Carter. He made
brigadier general in 1980, stayed at the White House into the Reagan
administration, then went to the Pentagon to serve as assistant
chief of the Army staff for intelligence 1981-85.
</TEXT>
