<2ND_LINE>AM-Mexico-Prison Riot,0387</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Authorities Probe Prison Riot</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TEPIC, Mexico (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Police on Sunday questioned four prisoners
and three guards suspected of helping stage a prison riot that left
24 people dead, officials said.
   They also were searching for two men who reportedly smuggled guns
into the prison by posing as lawyers, said state government
spokesman Francisco Flores.
   Ernesti Medina, assistant director of criminal investigation,
said police were questioning all the prison guards Sunday about the
events that began Thursday morning with a shootout in which the
warden was killed and ended Friday night in a bloody commando
storming of the building.
   All those injured _ three hostages, two prisoners and a guard _
were released from the hospital Saturday, Medina said.
   Flores said police Friday night arrested four inmates and three
prison guards, including the one who was injured. The inmates were
found in the prison's administrative offices during the rescue
operation, he said.
   Other hostages escaped unharmed.
   According to officials, the uprising was begun Thursday when
hundreds of relatives were visiting at the prison by six prisoners
mutinying because they were denied pardons given at Christmas to
those with good behavior.
   Helped by two well-dressed armed visitors, the inmates took over
warden Samuel Alvarado's office with 21 hostages. Alvarado, 31, was
shot in the leg and apparently bled to death.
   Special commando forces were flown in from Mexico City, 500 miles
southeast of the Venustiano Carranza penitentiary.
   Commando chief Jorge Armando Duarte was shot shortly before
nightfall Friday, when he went into the prison compound and tried to
talk the inmates into surrendering. ``The answer was a hail of
bullets which killed him instantly,'' said a state official.
   About two hours later, police lobbed dozens of tear gas canisters
into the penitentiary and rushed it with automatic weapons blazing.
An undetermined number of people died in the raid, which was
unsuccessful.
   About 11 p.m. Friday the commandos staged a second raid, which
killed more people and succeeded.
   At least two people besides the prison warden and commando leader
were killed before special forces stormed the inmates.
   The toll includes 19 prisoners and three unidentified people
presumed to be prisoners.
   The prsion's other 1,200 inmates remained under control
throughout the uprising.
</TEXT>
