<2ND_LINE>AM-Iran-Lebanon,0329</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>President Warns Shiites To Stop Fighting, Meets Cleric Rumored
Missing</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NICOSIA, Cyprus (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Ali Khamenei on Sunday warned
Shiite Moslem militiamen in Lebanon to stop fighting, saying they
should unify against the United States and Israel, the official
Islamic Republic News Agency reported.
   ``The Lebanese have a common enemy and should consolidate their
ranks against imperialism, Zionism and their mercenaries by
strengthening the Islamic aspects they share,'' said Khamenei,
according to the report monitored in Cyprus.
   The Iranian president made his remarks after meeting with the
acting chairman of the Lebanese Higher Supreme Shiite Council, Sheik
Mohammad Mehdi Shamseddine, the agency said.
   Shamseddine, the senior cleric on the council, has been on a
visit to Iran since early December. He arrived in Tehran just after
a bloody round of fighting between Lebanon's two main Shiite
militias to brief Khamenei on the latest developments in Lebanon,
the Iranian news agency said.
   The mainstream Amal militia, supported by Syria, has been
fighting the pro-Iranian Hezbollah, or Party of God, for control of
Lebanon's 1.2 million Shiites. Six days of fighting in Moslem west
Beirut last month left 40 people dead and 87 wounded, by police
count.
   Press reports in Lebanon have speculated that Shamseddine was
under house arrest in Iran because of what was termed his
``unexplained delay there.''
   The Lebanese weekly magazine, Ash-Shiraa, said in its latest
edition on Friday that the cleric's family and friends were worried
because he was scheduled to spend only one week in Iran.
   Amal and the Lebanese government consider Shamseddine the highest
Shiite religious authority in Lebanon. Hezbollah, the umbrella group
for many Shiite factions, does not recognize the authority of
Shamseddine and deals directly with Iran.
   Hezbollah has been trying to take over the highest post in the
council, which has been vacant since the disappearence of its
chairman, Imam Musa Sadr, during a visit to Libya in 1978.
</TEXT>
