<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Afghanistan     12-25 0399</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Afghanistan,0410</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Afghan Resistance Leader Meets Iranian President</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NICOSIA, Cyprus (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An Afghan resistance leader visiting Iran
to consult Afghan Shiite groups met Sunday with President Ali
Khamenei, who expressed hope for an Islamic government in
Afghanistan, Iranian news media reported.
   The visit to Tehran by resistance leader Burhanuddin Rabbani,
head of the Sunni Moslem Afghan alliance based in Pakistan, follows
Moscow's decision earlier this month to hold separate talks with
Afghan Shiite Moslems.
   Rabbani, whose group met for talks in Saudi Arabia with Soviet
officials, denounced Moscow's decision at the time, saying the
opening of a dialogue with two separate alliances would lead to
conflict and division in the decision-making process.
   Both alliances are fighting the Afghan government in Kabul that
is backed by thousands of Soviet troops.
   In his meeting with Rabbani, Khamenei said he hoped the
mujahedeen, as the resistance groups are called, will succeed in
establishing an Islamic government, said the official Islamic
Republic News Agency monitored in Nicosia.
   Earlier Iranian press reports quoted Rabbani as saying he was in
Tehran to consult with the Shiite alliance based in Iran in order to
determine the future of Afghanistan after the Soviet troop
withdrawal scheduled to end Feb. 15, 1989.
   Mohammad Javad Larijani, Iranian deputy foreign minister, on
Sunday expressed support for the talks between the Soviet Union and
the Afghan resistance, IRNA said.
   IRNA said Afghan refugees in Iran planned to stage a rally
Tuesday to mark the ninth anniversary of the Soviet military
intervention in support of the Marxist government in Kabul.
   In Rome Saturday, a top Soviet official held talks for the first
time with Mohammad Zaher Shah, former king of Afghanistan, who has
been mentioned as playing a possible role in a peace settlement,
officials said. The mujahedeen are opposed to any role for the king,
who has lived in Rome since his 1973 overthrow.
   Yuli Vorontsov, a first deputy Soviet foreign minister, said the
talks with the exiled king focused on a proposal for convening a
council in Afghanistan of 50 to 60 politicians or prominent
individuals to create a new government.
   More than 100,000 Soviet troops were deployed in Afghanistan
after December 1979 when they intervened to to back up a
Soviet-supported government. Moscow has delayed their scheduled
withdrawal, citing repeated guerrilla attacks. The mujahedeen were
not party to the withdrawal agreement signed in April in Geneva.
</TEXT>
