<HEAD>Other Nations Support Libya in Dispute With Washington</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NICOSIA, Cyprus (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Iran, Iraq and Syria rallied behind Libya
Sunday after the United States said it was considering destroying an
alleged chemical weapons plant in Libya.
   The Arab League scheduled a meeting Monday to discuss the issue,
according to an official Iraqi report.
   President Reagan said Thursday the United States and its allies
are considering using military force against a factory in Libya that
he said produces chemical weapons.
   The United States bombed Libya in 1986 in retaliation for a
terrorist attack on a Berlin disco that left a U.S. serviceman dead
and 204 other people wounded.
   Libyan leader Col. Moammar Gadhafi on Sunday denied Libya built a
chemical weapons plant and said the country was committed to U.N.
efforts to ban such weapons. Libya has said the plant manufactures
pharmaceuticals.
   In Iran, Tehran radio on Sunday quoted Deputy Foreign Minister
Hosseyn Sheykholeslam as saying his government supports Libya and
will take a ``firm stand in the face of America's threats and
propaganda attacks.''
   The official Syrian news agency SANA quoted an unidentified
government official as saying, ``Syria expresses its deep concern
and strong denunciation as to this unjustified campaign against
Libya.''
   The official Iraqi News Agency, INA, said Iraq agreed to
participate in the extraordinary session of the 22-member-nation
Arab League called by its secretary-general, Chedli Klibi.
   Libya asked for the meeting after Reagan made his threat, it said.
   ``By shouting these threats against the Libyan people, the
American administration is trying to impose the logic of terrorism
and aggression in solving bilateral and international issues,'' the
government-owned daily Al-Joumhouriya said in an editorial.
   Tehran radio criticized the United States for its failure to act
against Iraq, which earlier this year used chemical weapons against
its own dissident Kurdish minority.
   During the Iran-Iraq war, Iran supported Kurdish guerrillas
fighting for autonomy. Iraq started an offensive against Kurds soon
after Iran agreed to a cease-fire in the 8-year-old war in August.
   
   About 5,000 Kurdish civilians in the northeastern Iraqi town of
Halabja were killed by the chemicals.
   ``If the American government is really concerned about the
production of chemical weapons, why did it not react to the repeated
use of these weapons, especially by the Iraqi regime?'' Tehran radio
asked.
</TEXT>
