<2ND_LINE>AM-Guyana-US,0266</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Government, Forsaking Leftist Past, Asks Development Help From U.S.
Military</HEAD>
<DATELINE>GEORGETOWN, Guyana (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   In another sign that this South
American country is forsaking its leftist and anti-U.S. past,
domestic reports said Guyana has invited U.S. soldiers to drill for
water and help eradicate malaria next year.
   The state-owned Guyana Chronicle said in its weekend edition that
an advance contingent of senior U.S. Army officers from the
Panama-based Southern Command will arrive in Georgetown early next
month to complete details of the projects.
   Guyanese and U.S. Army officials held talks in July on U.S. aid
in drilling wells along Guyana's 235-mile coast and help in
eradicating malaria.
   The U.S. soldiers will also conduct dental clinics and treat
Guyanese for intestinal and skin diseases, the newspaper said.
   Defense Department spokesman William Caldwell said Sunday he knew
nothing of the projects. However, he said the holidays may have
delayed his notification.
   The aid project with U.S. soldiers contrasts sharply with the
anti-U.S. and socialist rhetoric of the 1970s and early 1980s under
late President Forbes Burnham.
   Relations have improved since President Desmond Hoyte took office
after Burnham's death in 1985. In September, Hoyte made a 12-day
trip to Washington.
   The governing People's National Congress has veered to the right
since Hoyte took over. He has encouraged foreign investment and
private enterprise in this finance-starved former British colony on
the northeast coast of South America.
   Opposition parties, led by the Marxist People's Progressive
Party, have called the projects with U.S. soldiers a violation of
Guyana's sovereignty.
</TEXT>
