<HEAD>Communist Rebels Vow Victory In 10 Years Despite U.S. Opposition</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 5th graf `Abcedes said...' to CORRECT name as per first
reference to Abcede, PICKS UP 6th `Last August...'</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT H. REID</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANILA, Philippines (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Communist rebels Sunday released six
soldiers captured in two separate September raids and predicted the
``total victory'' of their revolution within the next decade.
   Euclides Abcede, a former mayor who negotiated the release, said
the six sergeants were freed in Malinao village, about 70 miles
southeast of Manila.
   He said they were in good condition. Soldiers took the six to
Lucena City, 20 miles west of the release point, where they were
reunited with their families, he said.
   The freed men included five members of an engineering battalion
who were abducted Sept. 25 in Atimonan town where they were to
deliver the unit payroll. The sixth soldier, a Philippine
constabulary sergeant, was captured in a raid three days later on
the town of San Andres.
   Abcede said the army kept relatives of those freed away from the
release point, apparently to play down the affair.
   Last August, rebels in the same province freed four lieutenants
and a sergeant after protracted negotiations which were widely
reported in the Manila press. Their release ceremony won lots of
publicity and relatives of the freed soldiers were quoted last
August as expressing gratitude and admiration for the rebel New
People's Army.
   Military officials later complained the press had given the
insurgents a propaganda victory.
   The central committee of the banned Communist Party of the
Philippines on Sunday predicted victory within the next decade ``so
long as no grave errors of ideological subjectivism, political
opportunism, sectarianism and laxity are committed.''
   ``In twenty years of existence, the party remains at the center
of the national political stage, no matter how the United States and
its reactionary agents try to marginalize it through violence and
deception,'' the committee said in a statement on the eve of the
20th anniversary of the founding of the Maoist party. ``There is no
way the United States can defeat a resolute, protracted people's war
in the Philippines.''
   The statement claimed the party had grown from 60 ``red
fighters'' on Dec. 26, 1968, to 35,000 full time members and a
10-million-strong ``mass base,'' or sympathizers, operating in 63 of
the 73 provinces.
</TEXT>
