<HEAD>Auxiliary Bishop Condemns Car Bombings By Leftists</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SAN SALVADOR, El Salvador (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A high-ranking Roman Catholic
leader called on leftist rebels Sunday to give up car bombings in
their war against the government because the blasts have killed
civilians.
   Rebels set off four car bombs Friday near the heavily-fortified
Defense Ministry and Joint Chiefs of Staff headquarters in San
Salvador during one of their most dramatic attacks in the 9-year-old
conflict. They also launched bombs by catapult over the 20-foot-high
walls.
   Three people, all civilians, were killed and 38 wounded in the
attack.
   ``We characterize the attack on the Joint Chiefs of Staff as a
terrorist act because all the victims were civilians,'' Mons.
Gregorio Rosa Chavez, the auxiliary archbishop of San Salvador, said
Sunday.
   ``Since the first use of car bombs (in April), the church raised
its voice to denounce it as a negative development because it raised
the level of danger for the civilian population,'' he told reporters
at the capital's Catholic cathedral after a morning Christmas Mass.
   ``We believe it is an unjustifiable form of war and that it must
stop,'' he said.
   Rebels have detonated at least nine car bombs this year. The
rebels say the latest attack showed their strength, but the military
says the terrorist tactics by the rebels demonstrate their weakness.
   
