<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Haiti-Soldiers     12-25 0277</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Haiti-Soldiers,0285</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Charges Dropped Against Alleged Coup Leaders</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   PORT-AU-PRINCE, Haiti (AP) _ Charges against nine soldiers
accused of fomenting an October coup attempt were dropped and four
of them who had been jailed were released Sunday, the government
said.
   One of the four soldiers released Sunday, Sgt. Frantz Beauchard,
was accused of being the plot's instigator. The five other accused
soldiers are believed to have been in hiding since October.
   ``The President of the Republic, by this act of clemency towards
these former members of the Haitian Armed Forces, again shows his
firm will to safeguard peace, love, and harmony among all Haitian
families,'' said a release signed by Information Minister Antony
Saint-Pierre and read by state televison on Christmas day.
   On Wednesday the government released 12 other soldiers jailed for
their part in the alleged coup attempt, saying they had been
hoodwinked by the nine leaders of the plot. The 12 released
Wednesday and the four released Sunday had been jailed since
mid-October.
   The 21 soldiers have been discharged from the army.
   Rank-and-file troops, fed up with state-sponsored violence,
ousted former ruler Lt. Gen. Henri Namphy on Sept. 17 and replaced
him with Lt. Gen. Prosper Avril. The soldiers, who also ousted
nearly 60 unpopular officers, demanded a return to democracy and
respect for human rights.
   Several leftist groups, as well as the 12 soldiers released
Wednesday, claimed the soldiers' arrest in October was aimed at
purging the army of its most progressive elements responsible for
leading the Sept. 17 rebellion rather than foiling an attempted coup.
   Namphy had come to power in 1986 when former dictator Jean-Claude
Duvalier fled to exile in France.
</TEXT>
