<FILEID>AP-NR-12-25-88 1804EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u a AM-WeatherpageWeather     12-25 0456</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Weatherpage Weather,0466</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bitter Cold, Winds and Snow Head to Northern Plains</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   A winter storm that dumped snow on much of the West edged toward
the northern Plains on Sunday, promising more snow and wind-chills
as low as 55 degrees below zero. Meanwhile, the East basked in
relatively mild temperatures and parts of Southern California were
drenched.
   A heavy snow warning was posted for the southwest mountains of
Colorado, where in Purgatory, 17 inches of new snow fell by midday
Sunday. Gothic had 15 inches and Wolf Creek received 14 inches.
   Winter storm warnings were posted for much of northern Arizona,
all of Utah, and south central Montana. Clarkston, Utah, received 14
inches of snow.
   As the western storm moved eastward, the Dakotas braced for heavy
snow and strong winds, with wind chills expected to drop as low as
55 degrees below zero Monday.
   The storm brought heavy rain in Southern California on Saturday
night and early Sunday. One site in northern San Diego County got 3}
inches of rain.
   But Christmas Day was mild in the East. Temperatures warmed into
the 80s in Florida, in the 60s in southern Virginia and the 50s in
New York City.
   Heavier rainfall during the six hours ending at 1 p.m. EST
included 0.29 inch at Crescent City, Calif., 0.17 inch at Corpus
Christi, Texas, and 0.15 inch at Salinas, Calif. Heavier snowfall
during the same period included 3 inches at Ely, Nev., and Hill Air
Force Base, Utah, and 2 inches at Pocatello, Idaho.
   Temperatures around the nation at 2 p.m. EST ranged from 5
degrees below zero at Thief River Falls, Minn., and Williston, N.D.,
to 85 degrees at McAllen, Texas.
   Monday's forecast called for snow through the northern Plains and
upper Mississippi Valley, the Rockies and intermountain West;
scattered snow through Michigan; freezing rain and snow through
southern Wisconsin and Iowa; rain from northern Kansas across
Missouri to much of Illinois; rain scattered from Southern
California through the desert Southwest, southern New Mexico and the
southern Plains to Arkansas and western Louisiana; and a few
thunderstorms in the Great Plains and Mississippi Valley.
   High temperatures were forecast around zero over northern
Montana; in the single digits and teens from the intermountain West
through the northern Rockies and the Dakotas to much of Minnesota;
in the 20s and 30s from the Pacific Northwest through much of the
intermountain West, the central Rockies, Nebraska, the upper
Mississippi Valley, the Great Lakes region and the upper Ohio Valley
to the northern Atlantic coast; the 60s and 70s from the south
Atlantic coastal states through the Gulf Coast states to much of
Texas; and in the 40s and 50s across the rest of the nation.
</TEXT>
