<1ST_LINE>r a AM-AbortionFires     12-25 0446</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Abortion Fires,0461</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Three Abortion Clinics Damaged In Christmas Blazes</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KELLEY SHANNON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DALLAS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Suspicious fires broke out at three abortion
clinics in less than an hour early Christmas morning, leading clinic
directors to blame anti-abortion activists for the damage.
   The Dallas Fire Department responded to blazes at North Dallas
Women's Clinic, the Fairmount Center Clinic and A to Z Women's
Health Services Sunday morning, Capt. Mike Southerland said.
   The causes of the fires remained under investigation, but
Southerland said arson is suspected.
   ``They are suspicious,'' Southerland said. ``Very possibly a
flammable liquid (was) involved.'' Damage was described as minor,
and there were no injuries.
   Dena Jackson, director of clinic operations for North Dallas
Women's Clinic, said someone apparently spread flammable liquid on
the carpet in the clinic's reception area then set it afire.
   Ms. Jackson said she does not know who set the fire, but ``I feel
that it goes right along with the rest of the anti-abortion violence
throughout the United States.''
   But officials at Operation Rescue, an anti-abortion group that
protested at the North Dallas clinic Dec. 17, disagreed.
   Flip Benham, a spokesman for Dallas Rescue, the local chapter of
Operation Rescue, said he had not heard of the Christmas morning
fires at the clinics and said his organization would never resort to
such tactics.
   ``This is the first information that I have on it,'' Benham said.
``I am very saddened to hear that.''But he vowed that the group's
protests would continue.
   Betty Pettigrew, director of A to Z Women's Health Services, said
she believes also anti-abortion activists are responsible for the
damage to her clinic.
   ``We feel like we know who it is,'' Ms. Pettigrew said. ``They're
always threatening it, and we had heard that some clinic was going
to be hit _ not necessarily in Dallas.''
   She said fire investigators told her a five-gallon fuel can was
found near the entrance of the clinic and kerosene was poured in and
around the door to start the blaze.
   The fire at North Dallas clinic was reported shortly before 1
a.m., while reports of fires at the other two centers came about
1:30 a.m., Southerland said. All blazes were out before 2 a.m. and
none of the clinics sustained heavy damage, he said. No damage
estimates were made by clinic officials.
   Neither the North Dallas Women's Clinic nor A to Z Women's Health
Services will close because of the fires, the directors said. Ms.
Jackson said patients at her center will be cared for elsewhere this
week, but some office work will continue at the clinic.
   Officials of Fairmount Center Clinic did not immediately return
telehone calls.
</TEXT>
