<1ST_LINE>r a AM-JailDisturbance     12-25 0287</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Jail Disturbance,0295</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Overcrowded Georgia Jail Quiet After Christmas Eve Riot</HEAD>
<DATELINE>GAINESVILLE, Ga. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Inmates in the ``desperately
overcrowded'' Hall County jail rioted to make sure officials knew
how miserable they were, the sheriff said Sunday.
   ``Basically they were saying, `If we can't be home for Christmas
with our families, you won't be home with yours,''' Sheriff Dick
Mecum said after the Saturday night disturbance, which caused no
injuries but did extensive damage to the maximum security cellblock.
   Authorities calmed the prisoners within three hours and
transferred about 70 rioters to another north Georgia prison,
lowering the population in the Hall jail to 175. It was designed to
hold only 145.
   Mecum said the riot began about 8:30 p.m., when inmates began
burning mattresses, blankets and other flammable items in their
cells. Electrical and duct work in the ceilings was vandalized, and
some windows were broken.
   Mecum said the worst damage occurred in the maximum security
block, but some rioting spilled over into another block.
   Authorities went in first with the Hall County SWAT team, Mecum
said, and by 11 or 11:30 p.m., the last of the prisoners had given
up.
   Hall County administrator Mike Bryant said it was too early to
give a damage estimate.
   Coincidentally, Mecum wrote a guest column for the Sunday
editions of Gainesville's daily newspaper, The Times, taking the
state Department of Corrections to task for allowing prisons and
jails to become dangerously overcrowded. Like many county jails in
the state, the Hall jail houses many inmates for whom there is no
room in state prisons.
   ``County jails are desperately overcrowded every day, faced with
riots, fights, injuries and near loss of control of our individual
county facilities,'' Mecum wrote.
</TEXT>
