<FILEID>AP-NR-12-25-88 2003EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i AM-UN-Pickering 1stLd-Writethru a0705 12-25 0585</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-UN-Pickering, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0705,0600</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Choice Of Career Diplomat Reflects Bush View of U.N.</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS one graf for 3rd to ADD date that Bush selected
Pickering, PICKS UP graf 4 `Some former...'</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By VICTORIA GRAHAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>UNITED NATIONS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   For the first time in 20 years, the United
States has chosen a career diplomat as U.N. ambassador rather than a
high-profile political appointee.
   As president-elect, George Bush has moved away from the kind of
appointments that gave the U.N. post to Daniel Patrick Moynihan,
Andrew Young, Jeane Kirkpatrick, and Bush himself _ all members of
the president's Cabinet.
   On Dec. 7, Bush named Thomas Pickering, the U.S. ambassador to
Israel, to replace Vernon A. Walters, a former deputy director of
the CIA.
   Some former ambassadors made it clear they reported to the
president himself, not the State Department. But Pickering, unlike
his predecessors, will not be in the Cabinet and will report to the
assistant secretary of state for international organizations.
   Bush's said his choice ``symbolizes the importance I place on the
United Nations, as well as the Foreign Service.''
   Pickering is the first career diplomat to get the posting since
Charles Yost was appointed in 1969. They are the only two career
officers to hold the position since it was established 43 years ago.
   Ambassadors have included Henry Cabot Lodge, Adlai Stevenson,
Arthur Goldberg, George Ball, John Scali and William Scranton.
   Although U.S.-U.N. relations have been strained during the
eight-year Reagan administration, Bush has said the global situation
``makes the U.N. a more positive arena for constructive U.S. action
than it has been in recent years, offering greater opportunity for
vigorous U.S. leadership in dealing with critical global problems.''
   The choice of Pickering reflects the new importance the United
States accords the 159-member organization, which this year scored
successes from Afghanistan to the Persian Gulf to southern Africa.
   U.S. relations with the United Nations evolved from a love affair
to estrangement in the 1960s and 70s when the Soviet Bloc and
developing nations united to denounce the ``imperialist West.''
   Today, however, is an era of good feelings, respect for the world
body and no more name-calling. Improved U.S.-Soviet ties make the
United Nations an increasingly effective vehicle for tackling
international problems.
   Pickering, 57, has served as ambassador in Jordan and his
experience gives him extra credibility on the Middle East issue,
which figures prominently on the U.N. agenda.
   The Cabinet status for U.N. ambassador originated with Lodge, a
former presidential candidate who served from 1953 to 1960. Since
then no U.N. envoy, except Yost, settled for less in prestige,
salary and access to the president.
   But few observers see Pickering's posting as a downgrading of the
position.
   Ed Luck, president of the U.N. Association of the United States,
a pro-U.N. group, said it signifies ``a return to normalcy'' and a
commitment to use the United Nations to carry out foreign policy
objectives.
   ``He won't just give speeches defending our honor and
principles,'' he told The Associated Press.
   In the past, he said, ``there frequently has been some tension''
between the U.N. envoy and the administration, State Department or
Congress.
   Ms. Kirkpatrick was known for her combative speeches which
frequently pointed out the hypocrisy of some totalitarian regimes
criticizing the United States.
   Mark Franz, policy analyst at the conservative Heritage
Foundation, which frequently criticizes the world body, said
Pickering's appointment shows ``that Mr. Bush will be in charge.
U.N. policy will not be made by an individual, charismatic person ...
</TEXT>
