<1ST_LINE>r a AM-TankerExplosion     12-25 0289</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Tanker Explosion,0296</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Driver, Truck Passed Inspections Before Fatal Truck Crash</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MEMPHIS, Tenn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A roadside inspection the day before a
propane tanker truck exploded on an interstate, killing nine people,
found the truck was free of defects, a federal investigator said.
   National Transportation Safety Board investigators Saturday
released their initial findings of their probe into Friday's crash
of the truck on Interstate 240 in Memphis.
   The truck, carrying 9,500 gallons of the highly flammable
propane, skidded on a 25 mph exit ramp Friday, struck a retaining
wall and exploded.
   The dead included the driver of the truck, three occupants of
nearby houses that were set afire, and four people in other
vehicles. The ninth victim was another truck driver who died in a
crash that stemmed from the traffic jam that followed the first
crash.
   The propane truck had cleared an inspection Thursday by the
Arkansas Department of Transportation, James E. Burnett, head of the
NTSB investigation, said late Saturday.
   The driver, Randall Benson, 29, of West Memphis, Ark., was killed
in the crash. Burnett said Benson was thoroughly familiar with the
route along the accident site, was certified as medically fit to
drive hazardous materials, and had a good driving record with only
two minor accidents and no moving violations.
   ``Obviously, something happened,'' Burnett said. ``We're not
ready to say the driver lost control. It could have been something
else.''
   Burnett said the investigation is expected to take about nine
months. Gathering records regarding the investigation was hampered
because many offices were closed over the holiday weekend, he said.
   The interchange where the accident occurred has been criticized
as one of the most dangerous in the state. It is slated for a $100
million improvement.
</TEXT>
