<HEAD>Shamir Accepts Mubarak's Offer To Visit; Israel Prepares to Unveil
Peace Plan</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Prime Minister Yitzhak Shamir on Sunday accepted
Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak's offer to visit Israel to discuss
the stalled peace process, and Shamir said he is preparing to unveil
a new peace plan.
   ``I would be very happy to receive him (Mubarak) in Israel,''
Shamir said in Hebrew on Israel television's Arabic language news
service. ``I can not say that there will be full agreement between
us but I assume that we can advance the peace process.''
   Mubarak said Saturday that he would visit Israel if the meeting
would help peace efforts.
   Shamir also said he will soon reveal a new peace initiative and
hinted it will be based on the 1979 Camp David peace accords signed
by Egypt and Israel. Palestinians have rejected the accords, which
call for negotiations between Israel, Egypt and Jordan, and limited
self-rule for Palestinians in the occupied territories.Egypt and
Jordan have said the accord is outdated.
   An Israeli official in the Foreign Ministry said Shamir and the
Foreign Ministry are preparing new peace plans as a result of the
United States' meeting with the Palestine Liberation Organization
last week.
   ``We are all feeling the pressure to change the momentum,'' said
the official who spoke on condition of anonimity.
   Shamir reiterated his position that the PLO is not a partner for
peace talks and called on the United States to end its dialogue with
the organization.
   ``We ask the United States to correct the mistake that they have
made,'' he said.
   Shamir said Israel will work toward an agreement with Egypt and
Jordan toward self-rule in the occupied West Bank and Gaza Strip and
will permit free elections after an agreement is finalized.
   ``The first thing that will be done after signing the autonomy
agreement will be to have elections for an administrative council
that will administrate life in the area,'' Shamir said.
   ``This will become the legitimate representatives of the
Palestinan Arabs,'' he added.
