<HEAD>Africans Reported to Attack Chinese in Nanking</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An official report said Monday that African
students forced their way into a university dance in Nanking and set
upon those inside with iron bars, bottles and rocks. Thirteen people
were reported injured.
   African students have been involved in several violent incidents
over the past several years. Chinese authorities deny charges by
Africans who say they suffer from racism both on campus and in
Chinese society.
   The latest clash began Saturday evening when the Africans forced
their way through a door into the dance, and it lasted into early
Sunday, said the official Xinhua News Agency.
   The report said 11 Chinese employees from Hehai University in the
eastern Chinese city were injured, one seriously. Two Africans
sustained slight injuries in the melee, it said.
   Xinhua said the problem started when two African students
escorting Chinese women to the dance refused a request by university
doorkeepers to register the women's names.
   After the clash, a group of Chinese students held a street march
Sunday to demand that the attackers be punished, the report said.
   In May 1986, about 18 Africans studying in the northeastern city
of Tianjin fled to Beijing because of reported threats from Chinese
after a bottle-throwing battle.
   In 1980, 19 Africans and Arabs and 24 Chinese were injured in a
fight in Shanghai that began over loud music from a foreigner's
radio.
