<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Mexico-PrisonRiot 3rdLd-Writethru a0778 12-25 0866</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Mexico-Prison Riot, 3rd Ld-Writethru, a0778,0889</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Videotape Indicates Dead Inmates Were Alive And In Custody</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 12 grafs to RECAST lede with 23 dead, RAISE
location of uprising and reference to witness who heard later
gunfire, PICKS UP 12th pvs `The Venustiano...'</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By LINDAJOY FENLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MEXICO CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Five inmates arrested after a prison riot were
videotaped identifying themselves as prisoners later listed among 23
people killed in the uprising, raising the possibility they died in
custody.
   A Nayarit state judicial official reached by The Associated Press
on Sunday confirmed the men are now dead and said he did not know
how they could have died after being arrested.
   Officials at the prison at Tepic, the state capital about 500
miles northwest of Mexico City, said the death toll during the
two-day uprising was 23, with 19 of the deaths occurring Friday
night during two assaults by police.
   But a videotape shot by an NBC News camera crew and reviewed by
The Associated Press indicates there was only one assault and shows
at least 13 prisoners alive, flat on the ground, being questioned by
police.
   Five can be heard giving their names; those names are on a list
of dead given to The Associated Press on Saturday by an official
spokesman.
   A woman who had been held hostage told the AP in a telephone
interview Sunday that she was freed hours before what officials said
was the final guns-blazing assault.
   ``They (the prisoners) surrendered,'' said Brenda Margarita Rubio
Gonzalez, a prison records clerk.
   One witness told The AP that gunfire was heard inside the prison
after prisoners and then commandos went back inside the prison.
   ``I don't know what to say,'' said Ernesto Medina, assistant
director of criminal investigations, when asked about the videotape
on Sunday. ``I don't know anything about that.''
   Medina said he could not explain how the men could have died
after they were interrogated. He said that he had gone to the prison
at 11 p.m. Friday night and the prisoners were already dead when he
got there.
   Efforts to reach other state and federal officials by telephone
for comment were unsuccessful on Sunday, Christmas Day.
   The uprising began Thursday with a mutiny by prisoners angry that
they had been denied pardons. The prison warden was fatally wounded
at that time, officials said.
   The Venustiano Carranza prison was surrounded and two special
police teams, the Fox and Scorpion squads, were flown in from Mexico
City.
   According to the official version of events Friday night, the
commander of the Fox squad, Jorge Armando Duarte Badillo, was shot
to death by the mutinous prisoners while he was trying to talk them
into surrendering.
   Officials said the commando teams then launched an assault at
about 6 p.m. Friday that was repulsed, and finally launched another
attack at 11 p.m. Friday night that retook the prison administration
area and freed 19 hostages.
   However, NBC producer Oscar I. Delgado said a network camera crew
videotaped prisoners in custody at about 8:30 p.m. on Friday. The
prisoners had been brought into a park outside the prison, Delgado
said.
   Questioned on Sunday, Medina told The Associated Press that there
was only one assault, ``but it lasted a long time.''
   The death toll was initially given Friday night as six, but on
Saturday morning jumped to 22, then 24, with six listed as seriously
injured.
   The official death toll is now set at 23, Medina said Sunday,
including the warden, the police commander, and 21 prisoners.
   The videotape reviewed by the AP lasts a little over two minutes.
At least 13 prisoners can be seen lying on the ground surrounded by
police as officials move among them taking down their names.
   Although some of their clothing is ripped and at least two of the
prisoners appeared to have been wounded _ one had a bloody hand and
another a bloody face _ all were alive, lifting their heads to gaze
at the camera or answering questions from police.
   Sometimes a police officer can be heard kicking or poking a
prisoner, asking for a name or confirmation of a name as it is
written down. At one point a police official tries to halt the
taping, putting a hand over the camera.
   Five prisoners can be heard giving their names: Benjamin Gambero
Anzaldo, Jose Luis Parra Leyva, Arturo Torres Casillas, Ricardo
Hermosillo Guzman, and Enedino de la Cruz Simon.
   All five are on a list of dead provided Saturday to The
Associated Press by state spokesman Francisco Flores and confirmed
on Sunday by Medina.
   A witness to the events at the prison, who spoke on condition his
name not be used, said the prisoners were taken back into the
prison. This witness said that members of the Fox group re-entered
the prison at 10:00 p.m., and that shortly thereafter more than 30
shots were heard.
   Medina said Sunday that authorities were still questioning four
prisoners and three guards suspected of helping stage the riot. They
also were searching for two men who reportedly smuggled guns into
the prison by posing as lawyers.
   The prison's other 1,200 inmates remained under control
throughout the uprising.
</TEXT>
