<HEAD>U.S. Doctor Recalls Hearing: `The Ground Collapsed And The Earth
Screamed'</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Vladmir is cq in 3rd graf</NOTE>
<HEAD>With AM-Soviet Earthquake, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LAWRENCE NEUMEISTER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   U.S. doctors who treated Armenian earthquake
victims learned how to ``make do and function in impossible
conditions'' but despaired after returing home that ``so much work
is left to be done,'' one of them said Sunday.
   An eight-with Armenian physicians and
hospitals in the Soviet republic, he said.
   ``So much work is left to be done. If we stop now, it will be a
sort of flash-in-the-pan type of effort,'' said Kvetan.
   ``Technologically, they are at least 20 years behind us,'' he
said. ``In terms of dedication, we cannot even come close to them.''
   During their stay, the team _ a technician, a pharmacist, a nurse
and five doctors _ treated hundreds of patients but found many
people ``chronically injured both physically and emotionally,''
Kvetan said.
   Ailments ranged from crush injuries such as kidney failure,
shock, respiratory failure and severe infections, he said.
   ``Some patients were trapped under rubble for up to 12 days lying
freezing on the ground, covered with cement and rock, not eating. We
had patients who had been dug up by their own family,'' he said.
   ``We learned you can stay up for 10 days with hardly any sleep if
you have to, that you can get things done even in the middle of
total chaos if you decide to do it,'' he said.
   ``We saw that medicine is an international science and physicians
are always able to work together. We saw we can improvise and make
do and function in impossible conditions.''
   Besides continuing to help Armenia, the doctors on the trip also
want to establish a ``flying critical care team'' to work with a
Seattle rescue and disaster unit they met in the Soviet Union, he
said.
